      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "5caf007d70bd4b91",
      "text": "Peirce wrote a remarkable essay [1] on the Boolean mathematics of a Sign that combines the properties of addition and negation. It is a portmanteau Sign in the sense of Lewis Carroll (See below and Section III). We do not have the capabilities to typeset the Peirce Sign of illation, but see right for a rendition of it.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "d05cd0a2fbf8de95",
      "text": "Instead, I shall use the following version in this text: [a]b. When you see [a]b in the text you are to imagine that a horizontal bar has been placed over the top of the letter “a”, and a vertical bar, crossed with a horizontal bar (very like a plus sign) has been placed just to the right of the “a” in such a way that the vertical bar and the horizontal overbar share a corner. In this way [a]b forms the Peirce Sign of illation, and we see that this Sign has been created by fusing a horizontal bar with a plus sign. The horizontal bar can be interpreted as negating the Sign beneath it.\nPeirce went on to write an essay on the formal properties of his Sign of illation and how it could be used in symbolic logic. Here is the dictionary definition of the word illation. Note that we have taken the “Sign of Illation” as the title of this section of the paper."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "5d28dafce8d96571",
      "text": "il . la`tion. [L. illation, fr. illatus, used as past participle of inferre, to carry or bring in] Inference from premises of reasons; hence that which is inferred or deduced. [2]"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "3d1a20d98309df2d",
      "text": "The Sign of illation enables a number of notational conveniences, not the least of which is that the implication “A implies B” usually written as “ A -> B” is expressed as “[A]B “ using the Sign of illation."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "7378322d18fad8c7",
      "text": "The Sign of illation is a *portmanteau Sign* in the sense of [[Lewis Caroll]] [3], [4] who created that concept in his poem “Jabberwocky” where one encounters a bestiary of words like “slithy” – a combination of lithe and slimy. A portmanteau is literally a coat and hat rack (also a suitcase), an object designed to hold a multiplicity of objects. Just so, a portmanteau word is a holder of two or more words, each justly truncated to fit with the truncate of the other. A modern version to contemplate is the word “smog” a combination of “smoke” and “fog”."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "231a8afe2e607ed9",
      "text": "It is this fitting together of the two words that is so characteristic of the\nportmanteau. It recalls the amazing doublings of nature that would use a mouth for\neating and speaking, a throat for breathing and drinking, and the amazing multiple\nuse of the DNA at biology’s core. In Peirce’s case of his portmanteau Sign of\nillation there is no truncation, but rather a perfect fit at the corner of the horizontal\noverbar as sign of negation, and the vertical plus sign as sign of “logical or”. The\ntwo fit into one Sign that can then hold neatly yet another meaning as a Sign of\nimplication."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "fa894810eb01e17b",
      "text": "It is the meaning of the Sign of illation as implication that Peirce takes as\nprimary. In his essay [1], he begins with this interpretation, deduces many\nproperties of the Sign from this interpretation, and only in the last paragraph does\nhe reveal that his Sign can be taken apart into a plus sign and overbar (interpreted\nas a negation). In the beginning he writes [1] […]"
